{
  "text": "We then investigated whether the Mn-induced accumulation of P and S were also involved in Mninduced inhibitory of primary root (PR) growth. For this purpose, five-day-old seedling were transferred to fresh 1/2 MS media containing only 1/10 of normal P or 1/10 of normal S. We found that PR growth showed a less inhibition by excess Mn in the P-deficient or Sdeficient medium ( Figure 3A, B) . These data indicated that excess Mn could induced secondary toxicity by disturbing nutrient accumulation in plants. [CITATION_1] found that increased P supply in soil results in reduced leaf Mn content in barley, ",
